# gen173 (code as KB): parrot0 parses a C snippet deterministically, asserts its
# structure into the same KB, and names the functions it DEFINES from the AST —
# a call (printf) and control-flow heads (for/if) are not functions. Honest when
# there are none.
> what functions does this define: int add(int a, int b) { return a + b; } int square(int x) { return x * x; }
< I read it as code: it defines add and square.
> which functions are defined: int main(void) { printf("hi"); return 0; }
< I read it as code: it defines main.
> what functions does this define: int x = 5;
< I read that as code, but I do not see any function definitions in it.
# gen174 (call graph): each call attributed to its enclosing function, from the
# derived code_calls/2 — nested calls caught, no-call functions honest.
> what does main call: int main(void) { greet(); cleanup(); return 0; }
< I read it as code: main calls greet and cleanup.
> what does add call: int add(int a, int b) { return a + b; }
< I read it as code: add does not call any function.
# gen175 (symbolic execution): compute a pure function's result on literal args
